This is a picture of a Burger King ad clip on Instagram. In the description, it states "Vietnamese Sweet Chilli Tendercrisp Burger".  Immediately, the video received a violent reaction because of disparaging Asian culture in general and Vietnam in particular.  Oddly, it was the same way D&G thought it was when using chopsticks to eat pasta to advertise in the Chinese market. Immediately, D&G lost its billion market by the boycott of Chinese people.  As for Vietnam, do we still want to hold a Burger King when they deliberately oppose the chopsticks that we (and our fathers) eat daily with their "superior" food?  We also use their products when they are showing a despicable colonial eye in the land that is providing them financial resources?  We also use Burger King's stuff when they arrogantly scold our culture, right on our land with confidence about the Vietnamese people craving their fast food?  The answer in consumer dynamics. If nationalism and cultural resistance are strong enough, Burger King will not make any money from Vietnam anymore. As China has beaten D&G.
